close_symbols: UtAssert_BeginTest (declaration / prototype, e.g., in the UtAssert header)
explanation: The only pointer-related expression in OS_Application_Startup is the string literal "SETUP" passed to UtAssert_BeginTest. To decide whether the call violates the MISRA rule (pointers should be const-qualified when possible) you must know whether UtAssert_BeginTest's parameter is declared as const-qualified (e.g., const char *). If the prototype uses a non-const pointer (char *) that suggests the API does not promise not to modify the data and therefore the function signature (not this call site) may violate the MISRA guidance. Conversely, if the prototype already uses const-qualified pointer, there is no violation at this call site. Additionally, you must inspect the function implementation to determine whether the routine actually modifies or stores a non-const reference to the passed string (if it modifies or stores writable pointers, const qualification may not be possible). Therefore include both the declaration/prototype (to check the param type) and the definition/implementation (to check actual mutation/usage) of UtAssert_BeginTest.
